        <exploration xml:id="exploration-vsf">
            <title>Trying Out Volume Scale Factors</title>
            
            
        <figure xml:id="interactive-volume-scale-factors">
            <caption>Interactive Exploration of Volume Scale Factors</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="volume-scale-factors" platform="jsxgraph" width="90%" aspect="16:9" source="jsxgraph/volume-scale-factors.js">
                <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-volume-scale" surface="jsxboard" aspect="16:9" />
                <instructions xml:id="volume-scale-instructions">
                    <p xml:id="auto_iamrjkq0">
                        Use the slider <m>k</m> at the top left to change the linear scale factor of the blue image cone. Notice how changing the linear scale factor affects both the radius (<m>r'</m>) and the height (<m>h'</m>) simultaneously.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_qa0ztr42">
                        Observe the dynamically calculated volumes on the left side of the board. As you adjust the slider, verify that the Volume Scale Factor is always exactly equal to the cube of the linear scale factor (<m>k^3</m>).
                    </p>
                </instructions>
            </interactive>
        </figure>
    </exploration>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction / Explain</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_ics8pi5v">
                <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ctnvs47g">
                <alert>Common Misconception:</alert> <q>If <m>\text{LSF} = 2</m>, <m>\text{VSF}</m> is NOT <m>2</m> and NOT <m>4</m> <mdash/> it is <m>8</m>.</q>. <q>Volume does NOT scale by the same factor as length. It scales by the CUBE.</q>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_diva609x">
                <alert>Reverse Application:</alert> <q>If <m>\text{VSF} = 64</m>, then <m>\text{LSF} = \sqrt[3]{64} = 4</m>.</q>
            </p>
        </axiom>

        <insight xml:id="auto_zhvql9df">
            <p xml:id="auto_ek10i7so">
                A volume scale factor is the cube of the linear scale factor, representing the ratio by which the volume of a scaled object changes compared to the original object. 
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_dpz1mjop">
                <alert>Key Formulas:</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ojb4etad">
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{VSF} = (\text{LSF})^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{VSF} = \frac{\text{Volume of Image}}{\text{Volume of Object}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{LSF} = \sqrt[3]{\text{VSF}}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_9ev2spr0">
                <alert>Complete Scale Factor Summary:</alert>
            </p>
            <table xml:id="auto_69obq2ih">
                <tabular halign="center">
                    <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                        <cell>Dimension</cell>
                        <cell>Scale Factor</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Length</cell>
                        <cell><m>k</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Area</cell>
                        <cell><m>k^2</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Volume</cell>
                        <cell><m>k^3</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
            <p xml:id="auto_vti55tsp">
                <q>When each dimension tripled (factor <m>3</m>), volume increased by <m>27</m> because <m>3^3 = 27</m>.</q>
            </p>
        </insight>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_q47ulo1l">
                <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_dxgw4ibc">
                Learners work through the following problems (see worked examples below):
            </p>
        </axiom>

        <example xml:id="auto_am7fxwjp">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_kkbjnor4">
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_1hgrg0fb">
                    The corresponding heights of two similar cylinders are <m>4\, m</m> and <m>5\, m</m>.
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_vzvn7o71">
                    (a). Find the ratio of their corresponding volumes.
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_flmob5pb">
                    (b).If the smaller cylinder has a volume of <m>1536\, m^3</m>, find the volume of the larger cylinder.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_2gpr3roa">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{(a).The ratio of the heights}= \amp \frac{4}{5}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Linear scale factor}= \amp \frac{4}{5}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Volume scale factor} =\amp (L.S.F)^3</mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp \left( \frac{4}{5} \right)^3</mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp \frac{64}{125}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Therefore ratio of the volumes } =\amp 64:125</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{(b). Volume of larger cylinder;} \amp </mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{\text{Volume of smaller cylinder}}{\text{volume of larger cylinder}} =\amp \text{volume scale factor}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \frac{1536}{\text{Volume of larger cylinder}}= \amp \frac{64}{125}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Volume of larger cylinder}= \amp \frac{(125 \times 1536)}{64}</mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 3000\, m^3</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="auto_19e5yqmi">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_lud0mq9w">
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_o2kn3eza">
                    The capacity of two similar containers are <m>288\, cm^3</m> and <m>4500\, cm^3</m>.Find the ratio of their:
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_su89h4cc">
                    (a). Heights
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_wk3p9sm4">
                    (b). If the area of the smaller container is <m>140\, cm^2</m>, find the area of the larger container.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_fv5m1wnq">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Volume scale factor} =\amp \frac{288\, cm^3}{4500\, cm^3}=\frac{8}{125}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Lenear scale factor}= \amp \sqrt[3]{\frac{8}{125}}.</mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp \frac{2}{5}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Therefore the ratio of the heights} =\amp 2:5</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_y3i3a7ry">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Area scale factor} =\amp \left( \frac{2}{5} \right)^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp \frac{4}{25}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Area scale factor} =\amp \frac{\text{Area of the smaller container}}{\text{Area of the larger container}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{4}{25} =\amp \frac{140}{\text{Area of larger container}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Area of larger container} =\amp \frac{(25 \times 140)}{4}</mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 875</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{The area of larger container}= \amp 875\, cm^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="auto_agwlqnqr">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_xb0czf0q">
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_dj402low">
                    Given that cone <m>A</m> and cone <m>B</m> are similar cones, and the volume of cone <m>A</m> is <m>150 cm^3</m>, calculate the volume of cone <m>B</m>.
                </p>

                <sidebyside>
                    <image width="30%">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        <latex-image label="cone1">
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                               % First cone (on the left) - Colorless (larger size)
                            \fill[white] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7) -- (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7) -- cycle;
                            \fill[white] (-2,0) -- (0,4) -- (2,0) -- cycle;
                            \draw[thick] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7);
                            \draw[dashed] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7);
                            \draw[thick] (-2,0) -- (0,4);
                            \draw[thick] (2,0) -- (0,4);

                            \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                            \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,4);
                            \node[below] at (1,0) {7 cm};

                            % Adding label A below the dashed horizontal line
                            \node[below] at (0,-1) {A};  % Label "A" at the center of the base

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                        
                    </image>

                    <image>
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        <latex-image label="cone2">
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                          % First cone (on the left) - Colorless (larger size)
                            \fill[white] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7) -- (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7) -- cycle;
                            \fill[white] (-2,0) -- (0,4) -- (2,0) -- cycle;
                            \draw[thick] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7);
                            \draw[dashed] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7);
                            \draw[thick] (-2,0) -- (0,4);
                            \draw[thick] (2,0) -- (0,4);

                            \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                            \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,4);
                            \node[below] at (1,0) {21 cm};

                            % Adding label A below the dashed horizontal line
                            \node[below] at (0,-1) {B};  % Label "A" at the center of the base

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                        
                    </image>
                </sidebyside>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_kmz0yoc3">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Linear scale factor} =\amp \frac{7}{21}=\frac{1}{3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Volume scale factor}= \amp(\frac{1}{3})^3=\frac{1}{27} </mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{\text{Volume of cone A}}{\text{Volume of cone B}} =\amp\frac{1}{27} </mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{150}{\text{Volume of cone B}}= \amp \frac{1}{27}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Volume of cone B}= \amp 27 \times 150</mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 4050 cm^3</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

